04339nam a22005535i 9780822388456DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20062006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223884567 a10.1515/97808223884562doi  a(DE-B1597)553568  a(OCoLC)1097302820  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGN345b.O73 2006 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.012221 aOrtner, Sherry B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAnthropology and Social Theory :bCulture, Power, and the Acting Subject /cSherry B. Ortner. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA John Hope Franklin Center Book00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Updating Practice Theory -- tCHAPTER ONE. Reading America: Preliminary Notes on Class and Culture -- tCHAPTER TWO. Resistance and the Problem of Ethnographic Refusal -- tCHAPTER THREE. Identities: The Hidden Life of Class -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Generation X: Anthropology in a Media-Saturated World -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Subjectivity and Cultural Critique -- tCHAPTER SIX. Power and Projects: Reflections on Agency -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Anthropology and Social Theory the award-winning anthropologist Sherry B. Ortner draws on her longstanding interest in theories of cultural practice to rethink key concepts of culture, agency, and subjectivity for the social sciences of the twenty-first century. The seven theoretical and interpretive essays in this volume each advocate reconfiguring, rather than abandoning, the concept of culture. Similarly, they all suggest that a theory which depends on the interested action of social beings-specifically practice theory, associated especially with the work of Pierre Bourdieu-requires a more developed notion of human agency and a richer conception of human subjectivity. Ortner shows how social theory must both build upon and move beyond classic practice theory in order to understand the contemporary world.Some of the essays reflect explicitly on theoretical concerns: the relationship between agency and power, the problematic quality of ethnographic studies of resistance, and the possibility of producing an anthropology of subjectivity. Others are ethnographic studies that apply Ortner's theoretical framework. In these, she investigates aspects of social class, looking at the relationship between race and middle-class identity in the United States, the often invisible nature of class as a cultural identity and as an analytical category in social inquiry, and the role that public culture and media play in the creation of the class anxieties of Generation X. Written with Ortner's characteristic lucidity, these essays constitute a major statement about the future of social theory from one of the leading anthropologists of our time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822388456zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822388456423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822388456.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles